[Although the company did clearly modify production techniques that lowered the percentage of chicken contaminated by salmonella, the outbreak ended following the institution of a recall. - Mod.LL]

******
[2]
Date: Thu 31 Jul 2014
Source: The Oregonian [edited]
http://www.oregonlive.com/health/index.ssf/2014/07/usda_rejects_petition_to_ban_a.html


The U.S. Department of Agriculture rejected a petition on Thu 31 Jul 2014 to ban antibiotic-resistant strains of salmonella, the nation's leading food poisoning bug after norovirus. In a letter, the department told the Center for Science in the Public Interest that it needed more data to single out the strains as contaminants. The agency allows salmonella on raw poultry and meat, relying on consumers to kill the bacteria during cooking. The agency said there was no evidence that the antibiotic-resistant strains were resistant to heat.

The USDA "has no basis to conclude that properly cooking ground poultry, ground pork or ground lamb will not destroy salmonella, whether the strain is resistant or susceptible to antibiotics," the letter said.

The center, a well-known consumer advocacy group, petitioned the USDA 3 years ago, asking that it ban antibiotic-resistant strains of _S._ Hadar, Heidelberg, Newport and Typhimurium, which have all been associated with waves of illness, including the latest Foster Farms outbreak.

The center called the denial a setback. "USDA's failure to act on antibiotic-resistant strains of salmonella in the meat supply ignores vital information about the public health risk posed by these pathogens," said Caroline Smith DeWaal, the center's food safety director. "Despite numerous examples of outbreaks linked to resistant pathogens, USDA leaves consumers vulnerable to illnesses that carry a much greater risk of hard-to-treat infections, leading to hospitalization."

In 1994, the USDA banned a particularly virulent strain of _E. coli_, O157:H7, in ground beef. Then in 1999, it extended that the ban to non-intact beef products. And in 2011, the agency added 6 other _E. coli_ strains to the list, saying they cause serious illness and have a relatively low infectious dose.

Both the CDC and the WHO have sounded the alarm on antibiotic resistance, saying that, one day, simple infections could be deadly because physicians won't have any treatment options.

[Byline: Lynne Terry]

